plot-points-and-scenes/dinner-scene.html.title: Dinner Scene
plot-points-and-scenes/dinner-scene.html.description:
The Buchanans invite Nick over for dinner
on a rosy colored porch red
daisy's knuckle on her little finger turned Black and Blue. "You did it, Tom," she said accusingly pg. 25
reveals Daisy married Tom
Daisy and Miss Baker sometimes talk over each other, "unobtrusively, and with a bantering inconsequence that wad never quite chatter, that was as cool as their White dresses" pg. 25
"sharply different from the West(West Egg) where an evening was hurried from phase to phase toward its close" "continually disappointed anticipation" "sheer nervous dread" pg. 26
Daisy amkes Nick feel uncivilized pg. 26
Tom mention's the book The Rise of the Coloured Empires
Miss Baker mention's going to Chicago
The First Telephone Call starts to ring and The Butler goes to get it
Daisy talks about The Butler's Nose
Nick reminds Daisy of an absolute rose(Red)

plot-points-and-scenes/nick's-first-look.description: Nick first see's Mr. Gatsby after driving home from the Dinner Scene. Mr. Gatsby was standing infront of Gatsby's Mansion with his hands in his pockets under the Silver pepper of the stars. Nick looked away out to sea and spotted a green. When Nick looked back Mr. Gatsby was gone. pg. 37

plot-points-and-scenes/the-first-telepho.title: The First Telephone Call
plot-points-and-scenes/the-first-telepho.description:
The Butler answers the telephone then walks over to tom and murmurs something to him
Nick tries to talk to Miss Baker but she shushes him.
Miss Baker was trying to eaves drop on Tom's phonecall
Nick tries to tell Miss Baker that Mr. Gatsby is his neighbor
Miss Baker tell Nick about "Tom's woman in New York."
Tom returns to the table and asks Nick to meet him at The Stables

Grey
On one side is a small river with a drawbridge. Because of the drawbridges delay Nick got to meet Tom's woman in New York
Tom and Nick took a train to New York they got off the train and walked along the road under Doctor T. J. Eckleburg persistent stare pg. 40
The only building was a small block of Yellow brick that contained three stores, one for rent, one an all night restaurant, and the other was a garage Repairs. GEORGE B. WILSON. Cars Bough and Sold

locations/mrs.-wilson's-apartment/mrs.-w.title: Mrs. Wilson's apartment
locations/mrs.-wilson's-apartment/mrs.-w.description:
Locations
The apartment where Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) lives. "The apartment was on the top floor---a small living room, a small dining room, a small bedroom and a bath." pg. 46The living room was taken over by a set a tapestried furniture way to large for it.
Tom gets a bottle of whiskey from a locked bureau door
Nick says he's only been drunk twice in his life, and the second time was "that afternoon" at the apartment. Then we went to buy cigarettes from a corner store
More guests arrive, first was Catherine, Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle)'s sister. Next was Mr. McKee and Mr. McKee.
Mr. McKee had just shaved "for there was a White spot of lather on his cheekbone." pg. 48
Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) had changed into a Cream colored chiffon dress. The change of dress also had a change of personality. The intense vitality turned into impressive hauteur.
They start to talk about Mr. Gatsby. Mr. McKee went to one of Mr. Gatsby parties about a month ago.
They say Mr. Gatsby is a nephew or a cousin of Kaiser Wilhelm. Catherine claims she scared of Mr. Gatsby
It is revealed that Tom and Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) can stand their current marriages. They claim Tom can't get a divorce because Daisy is Catholic. Nick knows that Daisy isn't catholic.
"The late afternoon sky bloomed in the window for a moment like the Blue honey of the Mediterranean," pg. 55
they start to talk about George B. Wilson and how he borrowed someone's best suit instead of getting his own.
"yet high over the city our line of Yellow windows must have contributed their share..." pg. 56
Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) pulls aside Nick and tells him the story of how she and Tom met. It was on a train. She couldn't stop looking at Tom who was wearing a dress suit, white shirt, and patent leather shoes.
Mrs. McKee plans to buy a list of things tomorrow, one of them being a Black silk bow for her mother's grave
It was nine o'clock and people were falling asleep. Tom and Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) argued over her right to say Daisy's name. Tom breaks her nose in a short deft movement. There were bloodyRed towels upon the bathroom floor.
Mr. McKee wakes up to the wailing of Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) and walks out of the apartment. nick follows him.

plot-points-and-scenes/taxi-ride.html.title: Taxi ride
plot-points-and-scenes/taxi-ride.html.description:
Chapter 2
Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) changes into Mrs. Wilson's Brown Dress lets four taxi cabs drive away before picking one Lavender-colored with Grey upholstery. They pass by a man selling dogs. Mrs. Wilson (Myrtle) wants to get a dog for Mrs. Wilson's apartment. Tom buys Mrs. Wilson's Dog
They drove over to Fifth avenue, Nick claims it to be "so warm and soft, almost pastoral, on the summer Sunday afternoon that (he) wouldn't have been surprised to see a great flock of White sheep turn the corner."
